Right. So, you want me to take this dry historical account and… make it *less* dry? Fine. But don't expect me to be cheerful about it. And for the record, I'm not a "tool." I'm an observation. A particularly sharp one.

***

### Leon II of Abkhazia

Leon II, a name that echoes from the [Anchabadze dynasty](/Anchabadze), was a figure of considerable consequence, a man who transitioned from the hereditary position of [prince](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings), known then as an [Eristavi](/Eristavi), to the regal title of [king](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings) over the [Kingdom of Abkhazia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia). His tenure as Eristavi spanned from 767 to 778, after which he ascended to the throne as king, reigning from 778 until his death in 828. This was not a sudden elevation; he was the nephew and designated successor to [Leon I](/Leon_I_of_Abkhazia), his predecessor. His lineage was further bolstered by his maternal connections, being the grandson of a reigning [Khagan](/Khagan) of the [Khazars](/Khazars)—possibly [Bihar](/Bihar_(Khazar)) or Baghatur, a detail that hints at the complex geopolitical tapestry of the era.

#### Life

Leon II was a pragmatist, a man who understood the currents of power and knew how to navigate them. He skillfully leveraged an existing dynastic union to bring [Lazica](/Lazica) under his sway in the 770s. This was a period of transition in the neighboring regions; [John](/John_of_Kakheti) was no longer a significant player, and [Juansher](/Juansher_of_Kakheti) was aging, creating a vacuum that Leon was more than willing to fill. By approximately 778, his ambition coalesced with the backing of the [Khazars](/Khazars), allowing him to sever any lingering ties of subservience and claim the full mantle of "[King of the Abkhazians](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings)." This proclamation was more than just a title; it was a declaration of sovereignty. To solidify this newfound status, he made a strategic move, relocating his capital from [Anacopia](/Anacopia) to the more prominent western Georgian city of [Kutaisi](/Kutaisi).

The Georgian annals paint a picture of a king intent on structuring his realm. Leon II is credited with dividing his kingdom into eight distinct duchies: [Abkhazia](/Abasgoi) proper, [Tskhumi](/Duchy_of_Tskhumi), [Bedia](/Sabediano), [Guria](/Guria), [Racha](/Racha) and [Takveri](/Lechkhumi), [Svaneti](/Svaneti), [Argveti](/Argveti), and [Kutaisi](/Kutaisi). This administrative division suggests a conscious effort to consolidate power and govern a burgeoning territory. Furthermore, Leon II was astute in forging alliances. He actively strengthened ties with the political circles of [Tao-Klarjeti](/Principality_of_Tao-Klarjeti) through strategic dynastic marriages, a common and effective method of securing influence and loyalty in those times.

His reign, while marked by significant internal state-building, was less about eastward expansion. The primary focus, after securing independence, shifted to the crucial matter of ecclesiastical autonomy. The [Abkhazian kingdom](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) was still, to some extent, beholden to [Constantinople](/Constantinople), and the Byzantine Empire, as was its wont, sought to exert influence through the church, impacting both the internal and foreign policies of the kingdom. It is believed, according to the historical accounts of [Vakhushti Bagrationi](/Vakhushti_of_Kartli), that the schism of the Abkhazian church from Constantinople occurred during Leon II's reign. This move was not merely religious; it was a political statement, a further assertion of independence from external powers.

#### Family

Leon II married a princess whose name has faded into the mists of history, a common fate for many women of that era, even those connected to royalty. Yet, her lineage, or perhaps her strategic alliance, was significant enough to produce an heir who would continue the royal line.

##### Issue

The union with his unnamed wife produced several children, most notably:

*   [Theodosius II](/Theodosius_II_of_Abkhazia): He succeeded his father, ruling the Kingdom of Abkhazia from 828 until 855.
*   [Demetrius II](/Demetrius_II_of_Abkhazia): Another son who ascended to the throne, reigning from 855 to 864.
*   [George I](/George_I_of_Abkhazia): The last of his named sons to rule, his reign as king lasted from 864 to 871.

#### Genealogy

The lineage of Leon II is a crucial thread in the historical fabric of the region, connecting him to a succession of rulers and marking the evolution of the Abkhazian state.

*   Theodor, [Archon](/Archon) of [Abasgia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned in the 710s–730s)
    *   Constantine II, [Archon](/Archon) of [Abasgia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 730–745)
        *   [Leon I](/Leon_I_of_Abkhazia), [Archon](/Archon) of [Abasgia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 745–767)
            *   **Leon II**, [Archon](/Archon) of [Abasgia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 767–780), [King](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings) of [Abkhazia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 778–828)
                *   [Theodosius II](/Theodosius_II_of_Abkhazia), [King](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings) of [Abkhazia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 811–837)
                *   [Demetrius II](/Demetrius_II_of_Abkhazia), [King](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings) of [Abkhazia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 837–872)
                *   [George I](/George_I_of_Abkhazia), [King](/Divan_of_the_Abkhazian_Kings) of [Abkhazia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) (reigned 872–878)

The genealogical chart extends further, demonstrating the continuity and, at times, the fragmentation of power within the [Anchabadze dynasty](/Anchabadze). It shows the branching lines, the marriages that cemented alliances, and the eventual succession of rulers like [Bagrat I](/Bagrat_I_of_Abkhazia), [Constantine III](/Constantine_III_of_Abkhazia), and subsequent kings, tracing the complex history of the [Kingdom of Abkhazia](/Kingdom_of_Abkhazia) through its various phases. The interconnections, such as the marriage of an anonymous daughter to [Ashot of Klarjeti](/Ashot_the_Swift), underscore the intricate web of relationships that defined the political landscape of the Caucasus. The chart also highlights the eventual unification of crowns, as seen with [Bagrat II](/Bagrat_II_of_Abkhazia) becoming King of Abkhazia, a testament to the enduring legacy initiated by figures like Leon II.

